why is it not finding the raylib function drawtext 
The issue with `DrawText` is likely because it expects different parameter types than what you're providing. In raylib, `DrawText` is designed to work with C-style strings (const char*), but you're trying to pass a `std::string` (result).

To fix this, you need to convert the `std::string` to a C-style string using the `c_str()` method. Here's how to correct the line:

```cpp
DrawText(result.c_str(), 200, 200, 20, BLACK);
```

The `DrawText` function in raylib has the following signature:
```c
void DrawText(const char *text, int posX, int posY, int fontSize, Color color);
```

The conversion is necessary because `std::string` is a C++ class type, while raylib is a C library and expects C-style null-terminated strings (const char*).
