why doesnt drawtext display the result of the throw on the screen 
The issue might be because you're not actually storing the throw results in the `result` string at the right time. Looking at your code, you have a `ThrowResult()` method that builds the result string, but you're never calling it in your `Run()` method.

Try modifying your `Run()` method to call `ThrowResult()` when needed, especially after rolling the dice. Here's how you could modify the relevant parts:

```cpp
void DiceBoard::Run(){
    // ... other code ...

    if (rollAll.IsClicked()){
        RollAll();
        result.clear();
        result = ThrowResult(); // Add this line to update the result string after rolling
    }

    // ... rest of your drawing code ...
    DrawText(result.c_str(), 200, 200, 20, BLACK);
    // ... rest of your code ...
}
```

Also, make sure that:
1. The `result` string variable is properly declared in your `DiceBoard` class header file
2. `getCharDiceState()` is actually returning the correct values
3. The position (200, 200) where you're drawing the text is visible on your screen
4. The text color (BLACK) contrasts with your background

If you're still not seeing the text, you might want to:
1. Add a debug message to print the content of `result` to make sure it contains what you expect
2. Try drawing some static text first to ensure the DrawText function works in that location
3. Make sure the dice values are actually changing when you roll them
when i call the function in run it infinitely repeats the process i want it to just store the values once
Ah, I understand the issue. If you're calling `ThrowResult()` directly in the `Run()` method, it will keep adding characters to the result string every frame. Instead, you should only update the result when the dice are actually rolled. Here's the corrected version:

```cpp
void DiceBoard::Run(){
    BeginDrawing();
    //Update

    dice.SetPos(20, 150);
    dice2.SetPos(50, 196);
    dice3.SetPos(150, 140);
    dice4.SetPos(105, 230);
    dice5.SetPos(175, 185);

    dice.Update();
    dice2.Update();
    dice3.Update();
    dice4.Update();
    dice5.Update();

    rollAll.Update();

    ClearBackground(RAYWHITE);
    //Draw
    DrawRectangle(10, 113, 213, 234, LIGHTGRAY); // Dice board
    DrawRectangle(10, 278, 213, 78, GRAY); // Dice board buttons space
    DrawRectangle(18, 286, 73, 63, BLUE); // Dice board buttons

    dice.Draw();
    dice2.Draw();
    dice3.Draw();
    dice4.Draw();
    dice5.Draw();

    if (rollAll.IsClicked()){
        RollAll();
        result.clear();        // Clear previous result
        result = ThrowResult(); // Get new result only when rolling
    }

    DrawText(result.c_str(), 200, 200, 20, BLACK);

    rollAll.Draw();

    EndDrawing();
}
```

This way, the result string is only updated when the roll button is clicked, not every frame. The text will persist on screen until the next roll, showing the last roll result.
